Title: Predicting Heart Disease using Health-related Factors¶

Introduction¶

Background¶

Heart disease is a major global health concern. Besides being responsible for a significant number of lives lost, it also brings about huge amounts of economic costs. For example, in 2013 to 2014, the annual direct and indirect cost of cardiovascular disease (CVD) and stroke in the United States was an estimated $329.7 billion, and they accounted for 14% of total health expenditures in 2013 to 2014 (Benjamin et al., 2018). Detecting it early is important for effective prevention and treatment. Our project will focus on creating a tool that determines whether an individual will develop heart disease by considering a range of health-related factors.

Questions we'll answer¶

Is it possible to develop a predictive model leveraging attributes in the Heart Disease dataset to forecast the likelihood of an individual having heart disease? Furthermore, what are the predominant factors that exhibit significant influence on the likelihood of an individual developing heart disease based on the available dataset?

Dataset we'll be using:¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/johnsmith88/heart-disease-dataset/

Features Included:¶

- age
- sex
- chest pain type: 0, 1, 2, 3
- resting blood pressure
- serum cholestoral in mg/dl
- resting electrocardiographic results - values 0, 1, 2
- maximum heart rate achieved
- exercise induced angina
- oldpeak = ST depression induced by exrcise relative to rest
- the slope of the peak exercise ST segment
- number of major vessels (0, 1, 2, 3) colored by flourosopy thal: 0 = normal; 1 = fixed defect; 2 = reversable defect

Note: The names and social security numbers of the patients were recently removed from the database, replaced with dummy values.ble defect ble defect

Method¶

Since the target class, whether the patient has heart disease, is a binary class, we decide to use KNN classifier.

Feature Selection¶

1. Number of features¶

Since we are planning to use KNN classifier to build our model, we should not have too many features.

This is because increasing the number of features will increase the dimension of the problem. Since KNN classifier makes prediction based on Euclidian distance, it will perform pooly in high dimensions (curse of dimensionality).

Therefore, we will only choose 2 features to build our model and eventually make predictions about whether the patient is likely to have heart disease on unseen data.

2. Dropping Binary and Discrete Features¶

Since KNN is a distance-based algorithm and assumes that all features contribute equally to the distance calculation, we decided to drop the binary features and discrete features. This is because and discrete features might not adhere to this assumption, especially if some features are more informative than others.

Therefore, the following features are dropped:

  • sex
  • chest_pain_type
  • fasting_blood_pressure>120mg/dl
  • resting_electrocardiographic
  • exercies_induced_angina
  • slope_of_peak_exercise_ST
  • major_vessels_num
  • thal

3. Splitting of dataset¶

We split our heart_data_scaled into training and testing data, with training data taking up 75% of the total data available:

The 75% trainig data proportion helps ensure that we have sufficient training data to build an accurate predictive model.

At the same time, we have 25% of the testing data which enables us to evaluate the performance of our model based on test score. If test score turns out to be poor, we will make necessary adjustments at the training stage to improve performance of our model as much as possible.

In [5]:
set.seed(1234)
hd_split <- initial_split(heart_data, prop = 0.75, strata = target)
hd_training <- training(hd_split)
hd_testing <- testing(hd_split)

4. Feature Selection Among the Remaing Features¶

Features remaining are:

  • age
  • resting_blood_pressure
  • serum_cholesterol
  • max_heart_rate
  • oldpeak

To make sure that all continuous features contribute equally to the distance equally, we create a recipe that normalizes the data:

In [6]:
heart_data_recipe <- recipe(target ~ age + resting_blood_pressure + serum_cholesterol + max_heart_rate + oldpeak, data = hd_training) |>
                       step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
                       step_center(all_predictors())

Then, we pass our heart_data into the recipe, to create a new dataframe that contains only scaled continuous feature:

In [7]:
hd_training_scaled <- heart_data_recipe |>  
                           prep() |> 
                           bake(hd_training)

Final Decision for Features¶

After looking at the above graphical representations, we've narrowed down to two following pairs of features and will choose one of the two:

  • max_heart_rate and serum_cholesterol
  • max_heart_rate and oldpeak

Eventually, we decided to choose max_heart_rate and serum_cholesterol. The main reason is that it seems that observation data is not very evenly distributed for oldpeak. Looking at the graph, there are way more observations with oldpeak value = -1 than that with other oldpeak values. We feel that this may have a negative effect on the accuracy of predictions in our model trained using the oldpeak feature.

KNN Model Building¶

  • Features we'll use:
    • serum_cholesterol
    • maximum heart rate achieved
    • (target: heart_disease)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We need to tune the hyperparameter (neighbors). We carry out the tuning process:

In [13]:
knn_tune <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) |>
       set_engine("kknn") |>
       set_mode("classification")
In [14]:
set.seed(1234)
hd_vfold <- vfold_cv(hd_training, v = 5, strata = heart_disease)

knn_results <- workflow() |>
       add_recipe(heart_data_recipe) |>
       add_model(knn_tune) |>
       tune_grid(resamples = hd_vfold, grid = 10) |>
       collect_metrics()
In [15]:
options(repr.plot.width = 8, repr.plot.height = 6)
accuracies <- knn_results |> 
       filter(.metric == "accuracy")

accuracy_versus_k <- ggplot(accuracies, aes(x = neighbors, y = mean))+
       geom_point() +
       geom_line() +
       labs(x = "Neighbors", y = "Accuracy Estimate") +
       scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 14, by = 1)) + 
       scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0.4, 1.0)) 
accuracy_versus_k

Based on the diagram, it looks like either neighbors = 1 or neighbors = 2 give the highest accuracy estimate. Since even number can lead to a draw, we choose neighbors = 1.

Model Building¶

Using neighbors = 1, we build our knn_spec model:

In [16]:
knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = 1) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("classification")

Fitting Training Data¶

In [17]:
knn_fit <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(heart_data_recipe) |>
  add_model(knn_spec) |>
  fit(data = hd_training)

Discussion¶

Findings¶

From Visualization¶

In the diagram named "How Serum Cholesterol and Max Heart Rate Affect Heart Disease", the color of the points indicates whether the individual has heart disease, with one color representing those with heart disease (the blue dots) and another color for those without heart disease (the red dots). There is nr strong pattern separating the two groups based on the combination of serum cholesterol levels and maximum heart rate achieved. Both red and blue dots are intermingled throughout the graph. Howev,,r we can still tell that there are more people with heart disease when cholesterol leves are low and max heart rate is high.

From Results¶

Our model predicts very well on training data, as indicated by the high accuracy score of 0.988.

Alignment with Expectations¶

The model aligns with our expectations of making good predictions of heart disease based on maximum heart rate and serum cholesterol levels. However, it is surprising how high the accuracy score is when we used our model on the test data.

Moreover, based on the diagram named "How Serum Cholesterol and Max Heart Rate Affect Heart Disease", it is also surprising how cholesterol level alone did not have a large impact on predictions of heart diseases. We expected that there would be a strong positive correlation between cholesterol level and heart disease (Mitchell et al., 2012).

Impacts of Findings¶

The prediction model we built works well on test set. However, it is unknown how it will perform on unseen real-world data when deployed. Taking into consideraton how our model works well and the limitations of not having more real-world data, we can build other models which do not get affected by the curse of dimensionality to incorporate other features. By feeding the new model larger amount of training data and testing it on larger amount of testing data, we will be able to obtain a model that make even better predictions.

Future Questions¶

The results of our study could also lead to new questions and further research. One possible direction is to improve tools that assess the risk of heart disease by focusing on the most important factors we find. We would strive to make these tools easy to use so that everyone can benefit from them and take steps to protect their health.
